{"title_page": "Micka\u00ebl Nogal", "text_new": "{{short description|French politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{ infobox Officeholder\n| name           = Micka\u00ebl Nogal\n| image          = Micka\u00ebl Nogal.jpg\n| caption        = \n| office         = Member of the [[French National Assembly]] for [[Haute-Garonne's 4th constituency]]\n| term_start     = 21 June 2017\n| predecessor   = [[Martine Martinel]]\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1990|11|26|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Toulouse]], France\n| party          = [[La R\u00e9publique En Marche!]]\n| profession     = \n}} \n'''Micka\u00ebl Nogal''' (born 26 November 1990) is a French politician of [[La R\u00e9publique En Marche!]] (LREM) who has been serving as a member of the [[National Assembly (France)|French National Assembly]] since the [[2017 French legislative election|2017 elections]], representing [[Haute-Garonne]]'s [[Haute-Garonne's 4th constituency|4th constituency]].<ref name=\"Bio\">{{Cite web|url=http://elections.interieur.gouv.fr/legislatives-2017/031/03104.html |title=Elections l\u00e9gislatives 2017 |accessdate=19 June 2017 |work=Ministry of the Interior |language=French}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nIn parliament, Nogal serves as member of the Committee on European Affairs. In addition to his committee assignments, he is part of the parliamentary friendship groups with [[Colombia]], [[Spain]] and [[Venezuela]].<ref>[http://www2.assemblee-nationale.fr/deputes/fiche/OMC_PA719520 Micka\u00ebl Nogal] [[National Assembly (France)|French National Assembly]].</ref>\n\nIn December 2018, Nogal was appointed by [[Prime Minister of France|Prime Minister]]\u00a0[[\u00c9douard Philippe]] to a conduct 6-month parliamentary mission \u2013 in support of ministers [[Jacqueline Gourault]] and [[Julien Denormandie]] \u2013 on the role of estate agencies, with the mandate to \"simplify the rental of housing and improve relations between landlords and tenants.\"<ref>[https://immobilier.lefigaro.fr/article/le-gouvernement-veut-reformer-les-agences-immobilieres_f0bd8088-fd4c-11e8-b5a2-b44637c34deb/ Le gouvernement veut r\u00e9former les agences immobili\u00e8res] ''[[Le Figaro]]'', 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, LREM group chairman [[Gilles Le Gendre]] appointed Nogal and [[Mich\u00e8le Peyron]]\u00a0as the parliamentary majority's [[rapporteur]]s on economic and health emergency measures amid the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in France]].<ref>Mathilde Siraud (31 March 2020), [https://www.lefigaro.fr/politique/coronavirus-en-premiere-ligne-deux-deputes-lrem-jouent-les-relais-avec-l-executif-20200331 Coronavirus: en premi\u00e8re ligne, deux d\u00e9put\u00e9s LREM jouent les relais avec l\u2019ex\u00e9cutif] ''[[Le Figaro]]''.</ref>\n\n==Political positions==\nIn July 2019, Nogal voted in favor of the French ratification of the [[European Union]]\u2019s [[Comprehensive Economic and Trade Agreement]] (CETA) with [[Canada]].<ref>Maxime Vaudano (24 July 2019), [https://www.lemonde.fr/les-decodeurs/article/2019/07/24/ceta-qui-a-vote-quoi-parmi-les-deputes_5493039_4355770.html CETA : qui a vot\u00e9 quoi parmi les d\u00e9put\u00e9s] ''[[Le Monde]]''.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[2017 French legislative election]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nogal, Mickael}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Deputies of the 15th National Assembly of the French Fifth Republic]]\n[[Category:La R\u00e9publique En Marche politicians]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|French politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{ infobox Officeholder\n| name           = Micka\u00ebl Nogal\n| image          = Micka\u00ebl Nogal.jpg\n| caption        = \n| office         = Member of the [[French National Assembly]] for [[Haute-Garonne's 4th constituency]]\n| term_start     = 21 June 2017\n| predecessor   = [[Martine Martinel]]\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1990|11|26|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Toulouse]] , [[France]]\n| party          = [[La R\u00e9publique En Marche!]]\n| profession     = \n}} \n'''Micka\u00ebl Nogal''' (born 26 November 1990) is a French politician of [[La R\u00e9publique En Marche!]] (LREM) who has been serving as a member of the [[National Assembly (France)|French National Assembly]] since the [[2017 French legislative election|2017 elections]], representing [[Haute-Garonne]]'s [[Haute-Garonne's 4th constituency|4th constituency]].<ref name=\"Bio\">{{Cite web|url=http://elections.interieur.gouv.fr/legislatives-2017/031/03104.html |title=Elections l\u00e9gislatives 2017 |accessdate=19 June 2017 |work=Ministry of the Interior |language=French}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nIn parliament, Nogal serves as member of the Committee on European Affairs. In addition to his committee assignments, he is part of the parliamentary friendship groups with [[Colombia]], [[Spain]] and [[Venezuela]].<ref>[http://www2.assemblee-nationale.fr/deputes/fiche/OMC_PA719520 Micka\u00ebl Nogal] [[National Assembly (France)|French National Assembly]].</ref>\n\nIn December 2018, Nogal was appointed by [[Prime Minister of France|Prime Minister]]\u00a0[[\u00c9douard Philippe]] to a conduct 6-month parliamentary mission \u2013 in support of ministers [[Jacqueline Gourault]] and [[Julien Denormandie]] \u2013 on the role of estate agencies, with the mandate to \"simplify the rental of housing and improve relations between landlords and tenants.\"<ref>[https://immobilier.lefigaro.fr/article/le-gouvernement-veut-reformer-les-agences-immobilieres_f0bd8088-fd4c-11e8-b5a2-b44637c34deb/ Le gouvernement veut r\u00e9former les agences immobili\u00e8res] ''[[Le Figaro]]'', 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, LREM group chairman [[Gilles Le Gendre]] appointed Nogal and [[Mich\u00e8le Peyron]]\u00a0as the parliamentary majority's [[rapporteur]]s on economic and health emergency measures amid the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in France]].<ref>Mathilde Siraud (31 March 2020), [https://www.lefigaro.fr/politique/coronavirus-en-premiere-ligne-deux-deputes-lrem-jouent-les-relais-avec-l-executif-20200331 Coronavirus: en premi\u00e8re ligne, deux d\u00e9put\u00e9s LREM jouent les relais avec l\u2019ex\u00e9cutif] ''[[Le Figaro]]''.</ref>\n\n==Political positions==\nIn July 2019, Nogal voted in favor of the French ratification of the [[European Union]]\u2019s [[Comprehensive Economic and Trade Agreement]] (CETA) with [[Canada]].<ref>Maxime Vaudano (24 July 2019), [https://www.lemonde.fr/les-decodeurs/article/2019/07/24/ceta-qui-a-vote-quoi-parmi-les-deputes_5493039_4355770.html CETA : qui a vot\u00e9 quoi parmi les d\u00e9put\u00e9s] ''[[Le Monde]]''.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[2017 French legislative election]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nogal, Mickael}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Deputies of the 15th National Assembly of the French Fifth Republic]]\n[[Category:La R\u00e9publique En Marche politicians]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Micka%C3%ABl_Nogal"}
{"title_page": "Origin of the Mapuche", "text_new": "[[File:Pueblos_indigenas_de_Chile-ver.svg|thumb|200px|Approximate extent of indigenous cultures in Chile at the time of the arrival of the Spanish. [[Picunche]], Mapuche, [[Huilliche people|Huilliche]] and [[Cunco people|Cunco]] are all part of the Mapuche macro-ethic group.]]\nThe '''origin of the Mapuche''' has been a matter of research for over a century. The genetics of the Mapuche do not show overly clear affinities with any other known indigenous group in the Americas, the same goes for linguistics where Mapuche language is considered a [[language isolate]]. Archaeological evidence shows Mapuche culture has existed in Chile at least since 600 to 500 BC. Mapuches are late arrivals in their southernmost ([[Chilo\u00e9 Archipelago]]) and easternmost ([[Pampas]]) areas of settlement, yet Mapuche history in the north towards [[Atacama Desert]] may be older than historic settlement suggest. The Mapuche has received significant influence from Pre-Incan ([[Tiwanaku]]?), Incan and Spanish peoples, but deep origins of the Mapuche predates these contacts. Contact and conflict with the [[Inca Empire|Inca]] and [[Spanish Empire|Spanish]] empires are thought by scholars such as [[Tom Dillehay]] and [[Jos\u00e9 Bengoa]] to have had a profound impact on the shaping of the Mapuche ethnicity. \n\nThus the Mapuches are considered of autochthonous origin, with some genetic studies and archaeological and linguistic hypothesis hinting an origin or influence from the [[Amazon rainforest|Amazon]] in the distant past.\n\n==Early theories==\n[[File:Diaguita bowl.jpg|thumb|right|Replica of a [[Diaguita]] ceramic bowl from northern Chile. [[Ricardo E. Latcham]]'s theory posits Mapuches intruded from the east into the southern Diaguita lands.]]\nA hypothesis put forward by [[Ricardo E. Latcham]], and later expanded by [[Francisco Antonio Encina]], theorizes that the Mapuche migrated to present-day Chile from the [[Pampas]] east of the Andes.<ref name=Bengoaorigen/> The hypothesis further claims that previous to the Mapuche, there was a \"[[Diaguita|Chincha-Diaguita]]\" culture, which was geographically cut in half by the Mapuche penetrating from mountain passes around the head of the [[Caut\u00edn River]].<ref name=Bengoaorigen/><ref name=Croese1985>{{cite book |last=Croese |first=Robert A.|editor1-last=Manelis Klein |editor1-first=Harriet|editor2-last=Stark|editor2-first=Louisa R.|date=1985 |title=South American Indian Languages: Retrospect and Prospect |chapter=21. Mapuche Dialect Survey|location=Austin, Texas |publisher=University of Texas Press |pages=784\u2013801 |isbn=978-0-292-77592-3}}</ref> Albeit the Latcham hypothesis is consistent with linguistic features<ref name=Croese1985/> it is rejected by modern scholars due to the lack of conclusive evidence, and the possibility of alternative hypotheses.<ref name=Bengoaorigen/>\n\n[[Tom\u00e1s Guevara]] has postulated another unproven [[hypothesis]] claiming that early Mapuches dwelled at the coast due to abundant marine resources and did only later moved inland following large rivers.<ref name=BengoaAntiguo33-34>Bengoa 2003, pp. 33\u201334.</ref> Guevara adds that Mapuches would be descendants of northern [[Chango people|Changos]], a poorly known coastal people, who moved southwards.<ref name=BengoaAntiguo52>Bengoa 2003, p. 52.</ref> This hypothesis is supported by tenuous linguistic evidence linking a language of 19th century Changos (called Chilueno or Arauco) with Mapudungun.<ref name=DAns1976>{{cite journal |url=http://www.estudios-atacamenos.ucn.cl/web%20est%20atac%2037/pdf/numero04/10Dans.pdf |title=Chilueno o arauco, idioma de los changos del norte de Chile, dialecto mapuche septentrional |journal=Estudios Atacame\u00f1os |year=1976 |pages=113\u2013118 |issue=4 |accessdate=February 22, 2014 |last=D'Ans |first=Andr\u00e9-Marcel |language=Spanish |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140304021124/http://www.estudios-atacamenos.ucn.cl/web%20est%20atac%2037/pdf/numero04/10Dans.pdf |archivedate=March 4, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==Archaeology and toponymy==\nArchaeological finds have shown the existence of a Mapuche culture in Chile as early as 600 to 500 BC.<ref name=Bengoaorigen>[[Jos\u00e9 Bengoa|Bengoa]] 2000, pp. 16\u201319.</ref> \nIn 1954 [[Grete Mostny]] postulated the idea of a link between Mapuches and the archaeological culture of [[El Molle culture|El Molle]] in the [[Transverse Valleys]] of [[Norte Chico, Chile|Norte Chico]].<ref name=MitoADN2017/> The Mapuche [[Pitr\u00e9n complex|Pitr\u00e9n ceramics]] slighly postdate the ceramics of El Molle with which it shares various commalities.<ref name=Rivera2004>{{cite journal |last1=Rivera D\u00edaz |first1=Mario A. |date=2004 |title=Una sinopsis de la prehistoria del Cono Sur: El concepto de marginalidad desde el formativo al contacto Europeo |url=http://dialogoandino.cl/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/DA-24-2004-07.pdf |journal=Di\u00e1logo Andino |volume=24 |language=Spanish |issue= |pages= |doi= |access-date=December 19, 2019 }}</ref> Various archaeologists are of the idea that El Molle culture is related to cultures of the [[Argentine Northwest]], chiefly Candelaria, which are in turn suggested to be related to more northern \"tropical jungle\" cultures.<ref name=Rivera2004/> [[Tembet\u00e1]]s, lower lip piercings usually associated with indigenous cultures of Brazil, findings have been reported in Central Chile with scholars differing if these elements the result of migrations or some other type of ancient contact with the Argentine Northwest.<ref>{{cite report |author= |author-link= |authors= |date= |title=Informe de la Comisi\u00f3n de Verdad Hist\u00f3rica y Nuevo Trato |chapter=Territorio y Tierras Mapuche |language=Spanish |url=http://www.memoriachilena.gob.cl/602/articles-122901_recurso_7.pdf |publisher= |page=726|volume=3 |docket= |access-date=December 21, 2019 |quote= }}</ref>   \n\nMapuche communities in southern Norte Chico \u2013that is [[Petorca]], [[La Ligua]], [[Combarbal\u00e1]] and [[Choapa River|Choapa]] \u2013 may be rooted in Pre-Hispanic times at least several centuries before the Spanish arrival.<ref name=Telles43>T\u00e9llez 2008, p. 43.</ref> Mapuche toponymy is also found throughout the area.<ref name=Telles43/> While there was an immigration of Mapuches to the southern Diaguita lands in colonial times Mapuche culture there is judged to be older than this.<ref name=Telles43/>\n\nArchaeological remains indicating cultivation in canalized fields and [[raised field]]s by the Mapuche imply these techniques were likely introduced either from [[Lake Titicaca]] in the [[Altiplano]] or the Amazonian lowlands.<ref name=dillroth2013>{{cite journal |last1=Dillehay |first1=Tom D.|author-link1=Tom Dillehay|last2=Rothhammer |first2=Francisco |date=2013 |title=Quest for the Origins and Implications for Social Rights of the Mapuche in the Southern Cone of South America |url= |journal=Latin American Antiquity |volume=24 |issue=2 |pages=149\u2013163 |doi= |access-date= }}</ref><ref name=wetland/>\n\nMapuches are late arrivals in [[Chilo\u00e9 Archipelago]] where there are various placenames with [[Chono language|Chono etymologies]] despite the main indigenous language of the archipelago at the [[conquest of Chile|arrival of the Spanish]] being [[mapudungun|veliche]] (Mapuche).<ref name=IbarBruce>{{cite journal |last1=Ibar Bruce |first1=Jorge |date=1960 |title=Ensayo sobre los indios Chonos e interpretaci\u00f3n de sus toponim\u00edas |url=https://semanariorepublicano.uchile.cl/index.php/ANUC/article/download/19032/20162 |journal=[[Anales de la Universidad de Chile]] |volume=117 |issue= |pages=61\u201370 |doi= |access-date= }}</ref> This is in line with notions of ethnologist [[Ricardo E. Latcham]] who consider the [[Chono]] along other sea-faring nomads may be remants from more widespread indigenous groups that were pushed south by \"successive invasions\" from more northern tribes.<ref name=TriRiv41>Trivero Rivera 2005, p. 41.</ref>\n\n==Genetic studies==\nGenetically Mapuches differ from the adjacent indigenous peoples of Patagonia.<ref name=Rey2013>{{cite journal |url= |title=HLA genetic profile of Mapuche (Araucanian) Amerindians from Chile |journal=[[Molecular Biology Reports]] |year=2013 | pages = 4257\u20134267 |volume=40 | issue =7|last1=Rey |first1=Diego|last2=Parga-Lozano |first2=Carlos|last3=Moscoso |first3=Juan|last4=Areces |first4=Cristina|last5=Enriquez-de-Salamanca |first5=Mercedes|last6=Fern\u00e1ndez-Honrado |first6=Mercedes|last7=Abd-El-Fatah-Khalil |first7=Sedeka|last8=Alonso-Rubio |first8=Javier|last9=Arnaiz-Villena |first9=Antonio |doi=10.1007/s11033-013-2509-3|pmid=23666052 }}</ref> This is interpreted as suggesting either a \"different origin or long lasting separation of Mapuche and Patagonian populations\".<ref name=Rey2013/> A 1996 study comparing genetics of indignous groups in Argentina found no significant link between Mapuches and other groups.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Goicochea |first1=Alicia Susana |last2=Soria |first2=Marcelo |last3=Haedo |first3=Ana |last4=Crognier |first4=Emile |last5=Carnese |first5=Francisco Ra\u00fal |date=1996 |title=Distancias gen\u00e9ticas en poblaciones abor\u00edgenes de la Argentina |url=https://revistas.unlp.edu.ar/raab/article/view/161 |journal=Revista Argentina de Antropolog\u00eda Biol\u00f3gica |volume=1|language=Spanish |issue=1 |pages= |doi= |access-date=December 1, 2019}}</ref> A 2019 study on the [[human leukocyte antigen]] genetics of Mapuche from [[Ca\u00f1ete, Chile|Ca\u00f1ete]] found affinities with a variety of North and South American indigenous groups. Notably the study found also affinities also with [[Aleuts]], [[Eskimo]]s, [[Pacific Islander]]s, [[Ainu people|Ainu]] from Japan, [[Negidals]] from [[Khabarovsk Krai|Eastern Siberia]] and [[Rapa Nui people|Rapa Nui]] from [[Easter Island]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Arnaiz-Villena |first1=Antonio |last2=Juarez |first2=Ignacio |last3=Lopez-Nares |first3=Adrian |last4=Palacio-Gr\u00fcber |first4=Jos\u00e9|last5=Vaquero |first5=Christian |last6=Callado |first6=Alvaro |last7=H-Sevilla |first7=Alejandro |last8=Rey |first8=Diago|last9=Martin-Villa |first9=Jos\u00e9 Manuel |date=2019 |title=Frequencies and significance of HLA genes in Amerindians from Chile Ca\u00f1ete Mapuche |url= |journal=[[Human Immunology]] |volume=80 |issue= |pages=419\u2013420 |doi= |access-date= }}</ref>\n\nBased on [[Mitochondrial DNA|mDNA]] analysis of various indigenous groups of South America it is thought that Mapuche are at least in part descendant of peoples from the Amazon Basin that migrated to Chile through two routes; one through the Central Andean highlands and another through the eastern [[Gran Chaco|Bolivian lowlands]] and the [[Argentine Northwest]].<ref name=MitoADN2017>{{Cite journal|title=\u00bfPuede el ADN mitocondrial proporcionar informaci\u00f3n sobre la etnog\u00e9nesis de los pueblo originarios chilenos?|journal=[[Chungar\u00e1 (journal)|Chungar\u00e1]]|last=Rothhammer|first=Francisco|last2=Puddu|first2=Giannina|trans-title=Can mitochondrial DNA provide information on the ethnogenesis of Chilean native populations?|last3=Fuentes-Guajardo|first3=Macarena|volume=49|date=2017|issue=4|language=Spanish|doi=10.4067/S0717-73562017005000028|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\n==Linguistics==\n{{multiple image\n   | footer    = Reconstructed distribution of the [[Arawakan languages|Arawakan]] (left) and [[Pano-Tacanan]] languages (right). Both language families have been suggested to be linked to Mapuche.  \n   | image1    = Arawak-Languages.png\n   | width1    = 165\n   | alt1      = Map of the Arawakan languages in South America\n   | caption1  = \n   | image2    = Pano-Takanan_languages.png\n   | width2    = 160\n   | alt2      = Map of the Pano-Tacanan languages in South America\n   | caption2  = \n  }}\nThere is no consensus on the linguistic affiliation of the [[Mapuche language]], ''Mapudungun''. In the early 1970s, significant linguistic affinities between Mapuche and [[Mayan languages]] were suggested.<ref name=Key1978/> Linguist Mary Ritchie Key claimed in 1978 that Araucanian languages, including Mapuche, were genetically linked to the [[Pano-Tacanan languages]], to the [[Chonan languages]] and the [[Alacalufan languages|Kaw\u00e9skar languages]].<ref name=Key1978>{{cite journal |url= |title=Araucanian genetic relationships |journal=[[International Journal of American Linguistics]] |year=1978 | pages = 280\u2013293 |volume=44 | issue =4|last=Ritchie Key |first=Mary |doi=10.1086/465556}}</ref> Croese (1989, 1991) has advanced the hypothesis that Mapudungun is related to the [[Arawakan languages]].\n\nMapuche language do have many words in common with [[Quechuan languages|Quechua]], [[Aymara language|Aymara]] and [[Puquina language|Puquina]]. This reflects however a later influence of Andean culture and perhaps migrating populations on the already existing Mapuche.<ref name=Moulianetal2015>{{cite journal |last1=Moulian |first1=Rodr\u00edgo |last2=Catrileo |first2=Mar\u00eda|last3=Landeo |first3=Pablo|author-link2=Mar\u00eda Catrileo |date=2015 |title=Afines quechua en el vocabulario mapuche de Luis de Valdivia |trans-title=Akins Quechua words in the Mapuche vocabulary of Luis de Valdivia |url=https://scielo.conicyt.cl/scielo.php?pid=S0718-48832015000200004&script=sci_arttext|journal=[[Revista de ling\u00fc\u00edstica te\u00f3rica y aplicada]] |volume=53 |issue=2 |pages= |doi=10.4067/S0718-48832015000200004 |access-date=January 13, 2019|language=Spanish|doi-access=free }}</ref> This [[areal feature|areal]] linguistic influence may have arrived with a migratory wave arising from the collapse of the [[Tiwanaku empire|Tiwanaku Empire]] around 1000 CE.<ref name=Moulianetal2015/><ref name=wetland>[[Tom Dillehay|Dillehay, Tom D.]]; [[Mario Pino Quivira|Pino Quivira, Mario]]; Bonzani, Ren\u00e9e; Silva, Claudia; Wallner, Johannes; Le Quesne, Carlos (2007) [http://www.dendrocronologia.cl/pubs/2007_Dillehay(AncientCultivatedWetlands).pdf Cultivated wetlands and emerging complexity in south-central Chile and long distance effects of climate change]. ''[[Antiquity (journal)|Antiquity]]'' 81 (2007): 949\u2013960</ref>\n\n==Historiography==\n[[File:MapvsInc.JPG|thumb|right|190px|[[Guaman Poma|Huam\u00e1n Poma de Ayala's]] picture of the confrontation between the Mapuches (left) and the [[Incas]] (right) during the [[Battle of the Maule]].]]\nA milestone in Mapuche ethnogenesis may have been their contact with [[Incas in Central Chile|Inca invaders]] which gave them a collective awareness distinguishing between them and the invaders and uniting them into loose geo-political units despite their lack of state organization.<ref name=BengoaAntiguo40>Bengoa 2003, p. 40.</ref>\n\nMany historians, such as [[Jos\u00e9 Bengoa]], are inclined to hold that the Mapuche proper welded into a single ethnic group during the [[Arauco War]] against the Spanish.<ref name=dillroth2013/> According to scholars [[Tom Dillehay]] and Francisco Rothhammer this view is supported by archaeology which indicates that formerly scattered indigenous populations begun to dwell in more dense population clusters are the result of warfare.<ref name=dillroth2013/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n*{{cite book |last=Bengoa |first=Jos\u00e9 |authorlink=Jos\u00e9 Bengoa |title=Historia del pueblo mapuche: Siglos XIX y XX |url= |accessdate= |year=2000 |edition=Seventh |publisher=[[LOM Ediciones]] |location= |isbn=978-956-282-232-9 |language=Spanish}}\n*{{cite book |last=Bengoa |first=Jos\u00e9 |authorlink=|title=Historia de los antiguos mapuches del sur |url= |accessdate= |year=2003 |edition= |publisher=Catalonia |location=Santiago |isbn=978-956-8303-02-0 |language=Spanish}}\n*{{cite book |last=T\u00e9llez |first=Eduardo |title=Los Diaguitas: Estudios |url= |year=2008 |edition= |publisher=Ediciones Akhilleus |location=[[Santiago, Chile|Santiago]], Chile |isbn=978-956-8762-00-1 |language=Spanish|page=}}<!--|accessdate=August 27, 2019 -->\n* {{Cite book|title=Los primeros pobladores de Chilo\u00e9: G\u00e9nesis del horizonte mapuche|last=Trivero Rivera|first=Alberto|publisher=\u00d1uque Mapuf\u00f6rlaget|year=2005|isbn=91-89629-28-0|language=Spanish}}\n\n{{Mapuche}}\n\n[[Category:Mapuche history]]\n[[Category:Origin hypotheses of ethnic groups|Mapuche]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Pueblos_indigenas_de_Chile-ver.svg|thumb|200px|Approximate extent of indigenous cultures in Chile at the time of the arrival of the Spanish. [[Picunche]], Mapuche, [[Huilliche people|Huilliche]] and [[Cunco people|Cunco]] are all part of the Mapuche macro-ethic group.]]\nThe '''origin of the Mapuche''' has been a matter of research for over a century. The genetics of the Mapuche do not show overly clear affinities with any other known indigenous group in the Americas, the same goes for linguistics where Mapuche language is considered a [[language isolate]]. Archaeological evidence shows Mapuche culture has existed in Chile at least since 600 to 500 BC. Mapuches are late arrivals in their southernmost ([[Chilo\u00e9 Archipelago]]) and easternmost ([[Pampas]]) areas of settlement, yet Mapuche history in the north towards [[Atacama Desert]] may be older than historic settlement suggest. The Mapuche has received significant influence from Pre-Incan ([[Tiwanaku]]?), Incan and Spanish peoples, but deep origins of the Mapuche predates these contacts. Contact and conflict with the [[Inca Empire|Inca]] and [[Spanish Empire|Spanish]] empires are thought by scholars such as [[Tom Dillehay]] and [[Jos\u00e9 Bengoa]] to have had a profound impact on the shaping of the Mapuche ethnicity. \n\nThus the Mapuches are considered of autochthonous origin, with some genetic studies and archaeological and linguistic hypothesis hinting an origin or influence from the [[Amazon rainforest|Amazon]] in the distant past.\n\n==Early theories==\n[[File:Diaguita bowl.jpg|thumb|right|Replica of a [[Diaguita]] ceramic bowl from northern Chile. [[Ricardo E. Latcham]]'s theory posits Mapuches intruded from the east into the southern Diaguita lands.]]\nA hypothesis put forward by [[Ricardo E. Latcham]], and later expanded by [[Francisco Antonio Encina]], theorizes that the Mapuche migrated to present-day Chile from the [[Pampas]] east of the Andes.<ref name=Bengoaorigen/> The hypothesis further claims that previous to the Mapuche, there was a \"[[Diaguita|Chincha-Diaguita]]\" culture, which was geographically cut in half by the Mapuche penetrating from mountain passes around the head of the [[Caut\u00edn River]].<ref name=Bengoaorigen/><ref name=Croese1985>{{cite book |last=Croese |first=Robert A.|editor1-last=Manelis Klein |editor1-first=Harriet|editor2-last=Stark|editor2-first=Louisa R.|date=1985 |title=South American Indian Languages: Retrospect and Prospect |chapter=21. Mapuche Dialect Survey|location=Austin, Texas |publisher=University of Texas Press |pages=784\u2013801 |isbn=978-0-292-77592-3}}</ref> Albeit the Latcham hypothesis is consistent with linguistic features<ref name=Croese1985/> it is rejected by modern scholars due to the lack of conclusive evidence, and the possibility of alternative hypotheses.<ref name=Bengoaorigen/>\n\n[[Tom\u00e1s Guevara]] has postulated another unproven [[hypothesis]] claiming that early Mapuches dwelled at the coast due to abundant marine resources and did only later moved inland following large rivers.<ref name=BengoaAntiguo33-34>Bengoa 2003, pp. 33\u201334.</ref> Guevara adds that Mapuches would be descendants of northern [[Chango people|Changos]], a poorly known coastal people, who moved southwards.<ref name=BengoaAntiguo52>Bengoa 2003, p. 52.</ref> This hypothesis is supported by tenuous linguistic evidence linking a language of 19th century Changos (called Chilueno or Arauco) with Mapudungun.<ref name=DAns1976>{{cite journal |url=http://www.estudios-atacamenos.ucn.cl/web%20est%20atac%2037/pdf/numero04/10Dans.pdf |title=Chilueno o arauco, idioma de los changos del norte de Chile, dialecto mapuche septentrional |journal=Estudios Atacame\u00f1os |year=1976 |pages=113\u2013118 |issue=4 |accessdate=February 22, 2014 |last=D'Ans |first=Andr\u00e9-Marcel |language=Spanish |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140304021124/http://www.estudios-atacamenos.ucn.cl/web%20est%20atac%2037/pdf/numero04/10Dans.pdf |archivedate=March 4, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==Archaeology and toponymy==\nArchaeological finds have shown the existence of a Mapuche culture in Chile as early as 600 to 500 BC.<ref name=Bengoaorigen>[[Jos\u00e9 Bengoa|Bengoa]] 2000, pp. 16\u201319.</ref> \nIn 1954 [[Grete Mostny]] postulated the idea of a link between Mapuches and the archaeological culture of [[El Molle culture|El Molle]] in the [[Transverse Valleys]] of [[Norte Chico, Chile|Norte Chico]].<ref name=MitoADN2017/> The Mapuche [[Pitr\u00e9n complex|Pitr\u00e9n ceramics]] slighly postdate the ceramics of El Molle with which it shares various commalities.<ref name=Rivera2004>{{cite journal |last1=Rivera D\u00edaz |first1=Mario A. |date=2004 |title=Una sinopsis de la prehistoria del Cono Sur: El concepto de marginalidad desde el formativo al contacto Europeo |url=http://dialogoandino.cl/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/DA-24-2004-07.pdf |journal=Di\u00e1logo Andino |volume=24 |language=Spanish |issue= |pages= |doi= |access-date=December 19, 2019 }}</ref> Various archaeologists are of the idea that El Molle culture is related to cultures of the [[Argentine Northwest]], chiefly Candelaria, which are in turn suggested to be related to more northern \"tropical jungle\" cultures.<ref name=Rivera2004/> [[Tembet\u00e1]]s, lower lip piercings usually associated with indigenous cultures of Brazil, findings have been reported in Central Chile with some scholars differing if these elements the result of migrations or ancient contacts with the Argentine Northwest.<ref>{{cite report |author= |author-link= |authors= |date= |title=Informe de la Comisi\u00f3n de Verdad Hist\u00f3rica y Nuevo Trato |chapter=Territorio y Tierras Mapuche |language=Spanish |url=http://www.memoriachilena.gob.cl/602/articles-122901_recurso_7.pdf |publisher= |page=726|volume=3 |docket= |access-date=December 21, 2019 |quote= }}</ref>   \n\nMapuche communities in southern Norte Chico \u2013that is [[Petorca]], [[La Ligua]], [[Combarbal\u00e1]] and [[Choapa River|Choapa]] \u2013 may be rooted in Pre-Hispanic times at least several centuries before the Spanish arrival.<ref name=Telles43>T\u00e9llez 2008, p. 43.</ref> Mapuche toponymy is also found throughout the area.<ref name=Telles43/> While there was an immigration of Mapuches to the southern Diaguita lands in colonial times Mapuche culture there is judged to be older than this.<ref name=Telles43/>\n\nArchaeological remains indicating cultivation in canalized fields and [[raised field]]s by the Mapuche imply these techniques were likely introduced either from [[Lake Titicaca]] in the [[Altiplano]] or the Amazonian lowlands.<ref name=dillroth2013>{{cite journal |last1=Dillehay |first1=Tom D.|author-link1=Tom Dillehay|last2=Rothhammer |first2=Francisco |date=2013 |title=Quest for the Origins and Implications for Social Rights of the Mapuche in the Southern Cone of South America |url= |journal=Latin American Antiquity |volume=24 |issue=2 |pages=149\u2013163 |doi= |access-date= }}</ref><ref name=wetland/>\n\nMapuches are late arrivals in [[Chilo\u00e9 Archipelago]] where there are various placenames with [[Chono language|Chono etymologies]] despite the main indigenous language of the archipelago at the [[conquest of Chile|arrival of the Spanish]] being [[mapudungun|veliche]] (Mapuche).<ref name=IbarBruce>{{cite journal |last1=Ibar Bruce |first1=Jorge |date=1960 |title=Ensayo sobre los indios Chonos e interpretaci\u00f3n de sus toponim\u00edas |url=https://semanariorepublicano.uchile.cl/index.php/ANUC/article/download/19032/20162 |journal=[[Anales de la Universidad de Chile]] |volume=117 |issue= |pages=61\u201370 |doi= |access-date= }}</ref> This is in line with notions of ethnologist [[Ricardo E. Latcham]] who consider the [[Chono]] along other sea-faring nomads may be remants from more widespread indigenous groups that were pushed south by \"successive invasions\" from more northern tribes.<ref name=TriRiv41>Trivero Rivera 2005, p. 41.</ref>\n\n==Genetic studies==\nGenetically Mapuches differ from the adjacent indigenous peoples of Patagonia.<ref name=Rey2013>{{cite journal |url= |title=HLA genetic profile of Mapuche (Araucanian) Amerindians from Chile |journal=[[Molecular Biology Reports]] |year=2013 | pages = 4257\u20134267 |volume=40 | issue =7|last1=Rey |first1=Diego|last2=Parga-Lozano |first2=Carlos|last3=Moscoso |first3=Juan|last4=Areces |first4=Cristina|last5=Enriquez-de-Salamanca |first5=Mercedes|last6=Fern\u00e1ndez-Honrado |first6=Mercedes|last7=Abd-El-Fatah-Khalil |first7=Sedeka|last8=Alonso-Rubio |first8=Javier|last9=Arnaiz-Villena |first9=Antonio |doi=10.1007/s11033-013-2509-3|pmid=23666052 }}</ref> This is interpreted as suggesting either a \"different origin or long lasting separation of Mapuche and Patagonian populations\".<ref name=Rey2013/> A 1996 study comparing genetics of indignous groups in Argentina found no significant link between Mapuches and other groups.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Goicochea |first1=Alicia Susana |last2=Soria |first2=Marcelo |last3=Haedo |first3=Ana |last4=Crognier |first4=Emile |last5=Carnese |first5=Francisco Ra\u00fal |date=1996 |title=Distancias gen\u00e9ticas en poblaciones abor\u00edgenes de la Argentina |url=https://revistas.unlp.edu.ar/raab/article/view/161 |journal=Revista Argentina de Antropolog\u00eda Biol\u00f3gica |volume=1|language=Spanish |issue=1 |pages= |doi= |access-date=December 1, 2019}}</ref> A 2019 study on the [[human leukocyte antigen]] genetics of Mapuche from [[Ca\u00f1ete, Chile|Ca\u00f1ete]] found affinities with a variety of North and South American indigenous groups. Notably the study found also affinities also with [[Aleuts]], [[Eskimo]]s, [[Pacific Islander]]s, [[Ainu people|Ainu]] from Japan, [[Negidals]] from [[Khabarovsk Krai|Eastern Siberia]] and [[Rapa Nui people|Rapa Nui]] from [[Easter Island]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Arnaiz-Villena |first1=Antonio |last2=Juarez |first2=Ignacio |last3=Lopez-Nares |first3=Adrian |last4=Palacio-Gr\u00fcber |first4=Jos\u00e9|last5=Vaquero |first5=Christian |last6=Callado |first6=Alvaro |last7=H-Sevilla |first7=Alejandro |last8=Rey |first8=Diago|last9=Martin-Villa |first9=Jos\u00e9 Manuel |date=2019 |title=Frequencies and significance of HLA genes in Amerindians from Chile Ca\u00f1ete Mapuche |url= |journal=[[Human Immunology]] |volume=80 |issue= |pages=419\u2013420 |doi= |access-date= }}</ref>\n\nBased on [[Mitochondrial DNA|mDNA]] analysis of various indigenous groups of South America it is thought that Mapuche are at least in part descendant of peoples from the Amazon Basin that migrated to Chile through two routes; one through the Central Andean highlands and another through the eastern [[Gran Chaco|Bolivian lowlands]] and the [[Argentine Northwest]].<ref name=MitoADN2017>{{Cite journal|title=\u00bfPuede el ADN mitocondrial proporcionar informaci\u00f3n sobre la etnog\u00e9nesis de los pueblo originarios chilenos?|journal=[[Chungar\u00e1 (journal)|Chungar\u00e1]]|last=Rothhammer|first=Francisco|last2=Puddu|first2=Giannina|trans-title=Can mitochondrial DNA provide information on the ethnogenesis of Chilean native populations?|last3=Fuentes-Guajardo|first3=Macarena|volume=49|date=2017|issue=4|language=Spanish|doi=10.4067/S0717-73562017005000028|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\n==Linguistics==\n{{multiple image\n   | footer    = Reconstructed distribution of the [[Arawakan languages|Arawakan]] (left) and [[Pano-Tacanan]] languages (right). Both language families have been suggested to be linked to Mapuche.  \n   | image1    = Arawak-Languages.png\n   | width1    = 165\n   | alt1      = Map of the Arawakan languages in South America\n   | caption1  = \n   | image2    = Pano-Takanan_languages.png\n   | width2    = 160\n   | alt2      = Map of the Pano-Tacanan languages in South America\n   | caption2  = \n  }}\nThere is no consensus on the linguistic affiliation of the [[Mapuche language]], ''Mapudungun''. In the early 1970s, significant linguistic affinities between Mapuche and [[Mayan languages]] were suggested.<ref name=Key1978/> Linguist Mary Ritchie Key claimed in 1978 that Araucanian languages, including Mapuche, were genetically linked to the [[Pano-Tacanan languages]], to the [[Chonan languages]] and the [[Alacalufan languages|Kaw\u00e9skar languages]].<ref name=Key1978>{{cite journal |url= |title=Araucanian genetic relationships |journal=[[International Journal of American Linguistics]] |year=1978 | pages = 280\u2013293 |volume=44 | issue =4|last=Ritchie Key |first=Mary |doi=10.1086/465556}}</ref> Croese (1989, 1991) has advanced the hypothesis that Mapudungun is related to the [[Arawakan languages]].\n\nMapuche language do have many words in common with [[Quechuan languages|Quechua]], [[Aymara language|Aymara]] and [[Puquina language|Puquina]]. This reflects however a later influence of Andean culture and perhaps migrating populations on the already existing Mapuche.<ref name=Moulianetal2015>{{cite journal |last1=Moulian |first1=Rodr\u00edgo |last2=Catrileo |first2=Mar\u00eda|last3=Landeo |first3=Pablo|author-link2=Mar\u00eda Catrileo |date=2015 |title=Afines quechua en el vocabulario mapuche de Luis de Valdivia |trans-title=Akins Quechua words in the Mapuche vocabulary of Luis de Valdivia |url=https://scielo.conicyt.cl/scielo.php?pid=S0718-48832015000200004&script=sci_arttext|journal=[[Revista de ling\u00fc\u00edstica te\u00f3rica y aplicada]] |volume=53 |issue=2 |pages= |doi=10.4067/S0718-48832015000200004 |access-date=January 13, 2019|language=Spanish|doi-access=free }}</ref> This [[areal feature|areal]] linguistic influence may have arrived with a migratory wave arising from the collapse of the [[Tiwanaku empire|Tiwanaku Empire]] around 1000 CE.<ref name=Moulianetal2015/><ref name=wetland>[[Tom Dillehay|Dillehay, Tom D.]]; [[Mario Pino Quivira|Pino Quivira, Mario]]; Bonzani, Ren\u00e9e; Silva, Claudia; Wallner, Johannes; Le Quesne, Carlos (2007) [http://www.dendrocronologia.cl/pubs/2007_Dillehay(AncientCultivatedWetlands).pdf Cultivated wetlands and emerging complexity in south-central Chile and long distance effects of climate change]. ''[[Antiquity (journal)|Antiquity]]'' 81 (2007): 949\u2013960</ref>\n\n==Historiography==\n[[File:MapvsInc.JPG|thumb|right|190px|[[Guaman Poma|Huam\u00e1n Poma de Ayala's]] picture of the confrontation between the Mapuches (left) and the [[Incas]] (right) during the [[Battle of the Maule]].]]\nA milestone in Mapuche ethnogenesis may have been their contact with [[Incas in Central Chile|Inca invaders]] which gave them a collective awareness distinguishing between them and the invaders and uniting them into loose geo-political units despite their lack of state organization.<ref name=BengoaAntiguo40>Bengoa 2003, p. 40.</ref>\n\nMany historians, such as [[Jos\u00e9 Bengoa]], are inclined to hold that the Mapuche proper welded into a single ethnic group during the [[Arauco War]] against the Spanish.<ref name=dillroth2013/> According to scholars [[Tom Dillehay]] and Francisco Rothhammer this view is supported by archaeology which indicates that formerly scattered indigenous populations begun to dwell in more dense population clusters are the result of warfare.<ref name=dillroth2013/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n*{{cite book |last=Bengoa |first=Jos\u00e9 |authorlink=Jos\u00e9 Bengoa |title=Historia del pueblo mapuche: Siglos XIX y XX |url= |accessdate= |year=2000 |edition=Seventh |publisher=[[LOM Ediciones]] |location= |isbn=978-956-282-232-9 |language=Spanish}}\n*{{cite book |last=Bengoa |first=Jos\u00e9 |authorlink=|title=Historia de los antiguos mapuches del sur |url= |accessdate= |year=2003 |edition= |publisher=Catalonia |location=Santiago |isbn=978-956-8303-02-0 |language=Spanish}}\n*{{cite book |last=T\u00e9llez |first=Eduardo |title=Los Diaguitas: Estudios |url= |year=2008 |edition= |publisher=Ediciones Akhilleus |location=[[Santiago, Chile|Santiago]], Chile |isbn=978-956-8762-00-1 |language=Spanish|page=}}<!--|accessdate=August 27, 2019 -->\n* {{Cite book|title=Los primeros pobladores de Chilo\u00e9: G\u00e9nesis del horizonte mapuche|last=Trivero Rivera|first=Alberto|publisher=\u00d1uque Mapuf\u00f6rlaget|year=2005|isbn=91-89629-28-0|language=Spanish}}\n\n{{Mapuche}}\n\n[[Category:Mapuche history]]\n[[Category:Origin hypotheses of ethnic groups|Mapuche]]\n", "name_user": "Sietecolores", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eArchaeology and toponymy", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Origin_of_the_Mapuche"}
{"title_page": "It's Never Too Late (1953 film)", "text_new": "{{short description|1953 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = It's Never Too Late\n| image          = It's Never Too Late (1953 film).jpg\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[Filippo Walter Ratti]]\n| producer       = [[Piero Regnoli]]\n| writer         = [[Charles Dickens]]<br>Filippo Walter Ratti<br>Piero Regnoli\n| based on       = {{Based on|''[[A Christmas Carol]]''|[[Charles Dickens]]}}\n| starring       = [[Paolo Stoppa]]<br>[[Guglielmo Barnab\u00f2]]<br>[[Marcello Mastroianni]]\n| music          = \n| cinematography = Carlo Carlini\n| editing        = \n| distributor    = \n| released       = {{film date|df=yes|1953}}\n| runtime        = 86 minutes\n| country        = Italy\n| language       = Italian\n}}\n\n'''''It's Never Too Late''''' ({{lang-it|'''Non \u00e8 mai troppo tardi'''}}) is a 1953 Italian [[comedy film]] directed by [[Filippo Walter Ratti]].<ref name=\"CITWF.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.citwf.com/film246017.htm |title=The Complete Index To World Film: It's Never Too Late |accessdate=15 March 2009|work=CITWF.com}}</ref> The film is based on the 1843 novella ''[[A Christmas Carol]]'' by [[Charles Dickens]].\n\n==Plot==\nAntonio Trabbi is a greedy old man with a very rough personality and obsessed by money. He deprecates charity and love and has no friends or love interest, being lonely and avoided by people. On Christmas Eve he is visited by the ghost of his former business partner, who warns him about his life-style and announces the visit of three spirits, who will show Antonio past, present and future [[Christmas]] days. During the night, the three spirits actually appear to Trabbi, showing him his sad past, the bad reputation he has with everyone and the bad outcome of his actions, which will lead him to a lonely death and to terrible punishments in Hell. When Trabbi wakes up he is greatly distressed by the visions and eager to change his life, starting with that very same Christmas Day.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Paolo Stoppa]] as Antonio Trabbi\n* [[Guglielmo Barnab\u00f2]]\n* [[Isa Barzizza]] as Rosanna Gennari\n* [[Luigi Batzella]] (as Gigi Batzella)\n* [[Sergio Bergonzelli]]\n* [[Lola Braccini]] as Antonio's mother\n* [[Arturo Bragaglia]] as L'omino\n* [[Enzo Cerusico]] as Antonio as child\n* [[Olinto Cristina]] as Franci\n* [[Giorgio De Lullo]] as The Strange Man in the Pub\n* [[Giulio Donnini]] as Orazio Colussi\n* [[Attilio Dottesio]] as The man who poses the riddle at the party\n* [[Leda Gloria]] as Anna Colussi\n* [[Susanne L\u00e9vesy]] as Giulia - Daniele's wife\n* [[Ellida Lorini]] as Rosanna as child\n* [[Marcello Mastroianni]] as Riccardo\n* [[Leonilde Montesi]]\n* [[Valeria Moriconi]] as Marta\n* [[Luisa Rivelli]]\n* [[Daniela Spallotta]]\n* [[Luigi Tosi]] as Daniele Trabbi\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of ghost films]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0046134|title=It's Never Too Late}}\n\n{{A Christmas Carol}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Its Never Too Late (1953 Film)}}\n[[Category:1953 films]]\n[[Category:1953 comedy films]]\n[[Category:Italian Christmas films]]\n[[Category:Italian films]]\n[[Category:Italian comedy films]]\n[[Category:Italian-language films]]\n[[Category:Italian black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Films based on A Christmas Carol]]\n[[Category:1950s Christmas films]]\n\n{{1950s-Italy-comedy-film-stub}}\n{{Christmas-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1953 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = It's Never Too Late\n| image          = It's Never Too Late (1953 film).jpg\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[Filippo Walter Ratti]]\n| producer       = [[Piero Regnoli]]\n| writer         = [[Charles Dickens]]<br>Filippo Walter Ratti<br>Piero Regnoli\n| based on       = {{Based on|''[[A Christmas Carol]]''|[[Charles Dickens]]}}\n| starring       = [[Paolo Stoppa]]<br>[[Guglielmo Barnab\u00f2]]<br>[[Marcello Mastroianni]]\n| music          = \n| cinematography = Carlo Carlini\n| editing        = \n| distributor    = \n| released       = {{film date|df=yes|1953}}\n| runtime        = 86 minutes\n| country        = Italy\n| language       = Italian\n}}\n\n'''''It's Never Too Late''''' ({{lang-it|'''Non \u00e8 mai troppo tardi'''}}) is a 1953 Italian [[comedy film]] directed by [[Filippo Walter Ratti]].<ref name=\"CITWF.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.citwf.com/film246017.htm |title=The Complete Index To World Film: It's Never Too Late |accessdate=15 March 2009|work=CITWF.com}}</ref> The film is based on the 1843 novella ''[[A Christmas Carol]]'' by [[Charles Dickens]].\n\n==Plot==\nAntonio Trabbi is a greedy old man with a very rough personality and obsessed by money. He deprecates charity and love and has no friends or love interest, being lonely and avoided by people. On Christmas Eve he is visited by the ghost of his former business partner, who warns him about his life-style and announces the visit of three spirits, who will show Antonio past, present and future [[Christmas]] days. During the night, the three spirits actually appear to Trabbi, showing him his sad past, the bad reputation he has with everyone and the bad outcome of his actions, which will lead him to a lonely death and to terrible punishments in Hell. When Trabbi wakes up he is greatly distressed by the visions and eager to change his life, starting with that very same Christmas Day.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Paolo Stoppa]] as Antonio Trabbi\n* [[Guglielmo Barnab\u00f2]]\n* [[Isa Barzizza]] as Rosanna Gennari\n* [[Luigi Batzella]] (as Gigi Batzella)\n* [[Sergio Bergonzelli]]\n* [[Lola Braccini]] as Antonio's mother\n* [[Arturo Bragaglia]] as L'omino\n* [[Enzo Cerusico]] as Antonio as child\n* [[Olinto Cristina]] as Franci\n* [[Giorgio De Lullo]] as The Strange Man in the Pub\n* [[Giulio Donnini]] as Orazio Colussi\n* [[Attilio Dottesio]] as The man who poses the riddle at the party\n* [[Leda Gloria]] as Anna Colussi\n* [[Susanne L\u00e9vesy]] as Giulia - Daniele's wife\n* [[Ellida Lorini]] as Rosanna as child\n* [[Marcello Mastroianni]] as Riccardo\n* [[Leonilde Montesi]]\n* [[Valeria Moriconi]] as Marta\n* [[Luisa Rivelli]]\n* [[Daniela Spallotta]]\n* [[Luigi Tosi]] as Daniele Trabbi\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of ghost films]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0046134|title=It's Never Too Late}}\n\n{{A Christmas Carol}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Its Never Too Late (1953 Film)}}\n[[Category:1953 films]]\n[[Category:1953 comedy films]]\n[[Category:Italian Christmas films]]\n[[Category:Italian films]]\n[[Category:Italian comedy films]]\n[[Category:Italian-language films]]\n[[Category:Italian black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Films based on A Christmas Carol]]\n[[Category:1950s Christmas films]]\n\n{{1950s-Italy-comedy-film-stub}}\n{{Christmas-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/It%27s_Never_Too_Late_(1953_film)"}
{"title_page": "Mange Tout", "text_new": "{{About|the album|other uses|Mange tout (disambiguation){{!}}Mange tout}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Mange Tout\n| type       = [[Album]]\n| artist     = [[Blancmange (band)|Blancmange]]\n| cover      = Blancmange - Mange Tout.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = May 1984\n| recorded   = August \u2013 November 1983\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[New wave music|New wave]], [[synthpop]]\n| length     = 43:26\n| label      = [[London Records]]\n| producer   = John Luongo<br/>[[Peter Collins (record producer)|Peter Collins]]<br/>[[Blancmange (band)|Blancmange]] & John Owen Williams\n| prev_title = [[Happy Families (album)|Happy Families]]\n| prev_year  = 1982\n| next_title = [[Believe You Me]]\n| next_year  = 1985\n}}\n\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|3|5}} <ref name=allmusic />\n| rev2      = ''[[Smash Hits]]''\n| rev2score = {{Rating|9|10}}<ref name=\"Smash Hits\">{{cite news |first=Lisa |last=Anthony |title=Album Reviews: Blancmange \u2013 ''Mange Tout'' |newspaper=[[Smash Hits]] |publisher=[[EMAP]] |location=London, England |page=27 |date=10 May 1984}}</ref>\n| rev3      = ''[[Record Mirror]]''\n| rev3score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite journal|last=Strike|first=Andy|date=19 May 1984|title=Albums|journal=Record Mirror}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Mange Tout''''' is the second [[album]] by the British [[synthpop]] duo [[Blancmange (band)|Blancmange]]. Released in May 1984, it was Blancmange's most successful album, peaking at number 8 in the UK album chart<ref name=\"officialcharts1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/19533/blancmange/ |title=BLANCMANGE &#124; full Official Chart History &#124; Official Charts Company |publisher=Officialcharts.com |date= |accessdate=2018-10-22}}</ref> and was certified Gold by the [[British Phonographic Industry|BPI]] for sales in excess of 100,000 copies.<ref>[http://www.bpi.co.uk/certifiedawards/search.aspx BPI Certifications Database] {{webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/6DaMNbmDo?url=http://www.bpi.co.uk/certifiedawards/search.aspx |date=2013-01-11 }}</ref> The album contained four UK Top 40 singles, two of which reached the Top 10.<ref name=\"officialcharts1\"/> The fourth single to be released and final track on the album is a cover version of [[ABBA|ABBA's]] penultimate single [[The Day Before You Came]]. \n\nIn addition to the usual vinyl and cassette release, a limited edition vinyl picture disc was also released. The album was later released on CD, and a 2-disc remastered Deluxe Edition was released by [[Edsel]] in 2008 which featured the album along with a second disc of remixes and B-sides.\n\n==Track listing==\nAll songs written by [[Neil Arthur]] & [[Stephen Luscombe]], except where noted.\n\n===LP: SH 8554===\n\n====Side 1====\n# \"[[Don't Tell Me (Blancmange song)|Don't Tell Me]]\" \u2013 3:31\n# \"Game Above My Head\" \u2013 3:58\n# \"[[Blind Vision]]\" \u2013 3:56\n# \"Time Became the Tide\" \u2013 4:49\n# \"[[That's Love, That It Is]]\" \u2013 4:22\n\n====Side 2====\n# \"Murder\" \u2013 5:58\n# \"See the Train\" \u2013 2:04\n# \"All Things Are Nice\" \u2013 4:59\n# \"My Baby\" \u2013 3:59\n# \"[[The Day Before You Came]]\" ([[Benny Andersson|Andersson]]/[[Bj\u00f6rn Ulvaeus|Ulvaeus]]) \u2013 5:50\n\n===CD: 810 235\u20132===\n\n===2008 Edsel - Remastered CD: EDSL 2023===\n# \"Don't Tell Me\" \u2013 3:31\n# \"Game Above My Head\" \u2013 3:59\n# \"Blind Vision\" \u2013 3:59\n# \"Time Became The Tide\" \u2013 4:50\n# \"That's Love, That It Is\" \u2013 4:20\n# \"Murder\" \u2013 5:58\n# \"See The Train\" \u2013 2:05\n# \"All Things Are Nice\" \u2013 5:01\n# \"My Baby\" \u2013 3:57\n# \"[[The Day Before You Came]]\" \u2013 4:25 (Anderson/Ulvaeus)\n# \"Game Above My Head (Long Version)\" \u2013 7:14\n\n===2008 Edsel - The B-Sides And Remixes CD: EDSL 2023===\n# \"Blind Vision (Long Version)\" \u2013 9:39\n# \"Heaven Knows Where Heaven Is\" \u2013 3:24\n# \"On Our Way To?\"